<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910923-0118</DOCNO><DOCID>910923-0118.</DOCID><HL>   Pay 'N Pak Stores,   Parent Concern, File   Chapter 11 Petition</HL><DATE>09/23/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C8</SO><CO>   X.PXT</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)</MS><IN>BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)SPECIALTY RETAILERS OF LIMITED PRODUCT LINES (OTS)ALL SPECIALTY RETAILERS (RTS)</IN><NS>BANKRUPTCY DECLARATIONS AND PROCEEDINGS (BCY)FINANCING AGREEMENTS (FNC)</NS><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)WASHINGTON (WA)</RE><LP>   SEATTLE -- Pay 'N Pak Stores Inc., operator ofhome-improvement stores in 14 western states, and its parentcompany, PNP Holdings Corp., filed for Chapter 11bankruptcy-law protection, company executives said.   Although Pay 'N Pak has been in negotiations withcreditors to restructure debt, the company said it couldn'tresolve all of the issues in time to assure financing formerchandise in the company's 78 stores.</LP><TEXT>   John H. Markley, chairman of Pay 'N Pak, said that inconnection with the filing the company reached an agreementwith a 10-member bank group, led by Manufacturers HanoverTrust Co., for $100 million in debtor-in-possessionfinancing. The new line of credit is an increase of $40million from the existing credit facility.   Mr. Markley said the new bank financing will give thecompany enough cash to purchase goods for the fall and springseasons and to increase levels of stock at the company'sstores.   The company took on a heavy debt load in 1987 as part of aleveraged buyout led by previous managers. In August, Pay 'NPak sold 24 of its least profitable stores in California aspart of a restructuring.   Under Chapter 11, a company is protected from creditorlawsuits while it works out a plan to pay its debts.</TEXT></DOC>